var documenterSearchIndex = {"docs":
[{"category":"section","location":"manual/internals/#Internal-Layout-and-Kernels","page":"Internal Layout and Kernels","text":"This page is for users who want to understand how FDGrids.jl works internally or contribute to the package. The main design goal is simple:\n\nStore only the coefficients that are actually used, but keep the storage regular enough that applying the operator is fast and predictable.\n\nThe two central types are DiffMatrix and AdjointDiffMatrix. They use different coefficient layouts because applying a forward finite-difference matrix row-by-row is different from applying its transpose.","title":"Internal Layout and Kernels"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/internals/#Forward-Operator-Layout","page":"Internal Layout and Kernels","text":"A DiffMatrix represents an N × N banded finite-difference matrix with a fixed stencil width WIDTH. Instead of storing the dense matrix, it stores exactly WIDTH coefficients per row:\n\nmathrmlength(Dmathrmcoeffs) = NmathrmWIDTH\n\nThe coefficients for logical row i occupy:\n\np_i = (i-1)mathrmWIDTH + 1\n\nso the stored slice is:\n\nD.coeffs[p_i : p_i + WIDTH - 1]\n\nThe logical dense row is reconstructed by placing those coefficients on the stencil selected for row i. For an interior row with HWIDTH = WIDTH ÷ 2, the stencil starts at:\n\ni - mathrmHWIDTH\n\nNear the left boundary, the stencil is shifted right. Near the right boundary, it is shifted left. Therefore the start column is:\n\nmathrmleft(i) =\nmathrmclamp(i-mathrmHWIDTH1N-mathrmWIDTH+1)\n\nThe dense interpretation is:\n\nD_imathrmleft(i)+k-1 = Dmathrmcoeffs_p_i+k-1\nqquad k = 1ldotsmathrmWIDTH\n\nAll other entries in row i are structural zeros.","title":"Forward Operator Layout"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/internals/#Example:-Width-5","page":"Internal Layout and Kernels","text":"For WIDTH = 5, each row stores five coefficients. The stencil positions look like this:\n\nrow 1:  x x x x x . . . .\nrow 2:  x x x x x . . . .\nrow 3:  x x x x x . . . .\nrow 4:  . x x x x x . . .\nrow 5:  . . x x x x x . .\n...\nrow N-2: . . . . x x x x x\nrow N-1: . . . . x x x x x\nrow N:   . . . . x x x x x\n\nThe compact coefficient vector stores these rows back-to-back:\n\nrow 1              row 2              row 3\n| c11 c12 c13 c14 c15 | c21 c22 c23 c24 c25 | ...\n\nThis row-major compact layout is what makes the forward multiplication simple: for output row i, read WIDTH coefficients, read WIDTH input values, take a dot product, and advance the coefficient pointer by WIDTH.","title":"Example: Width 5"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/internals/#Forward-Matrix-Multiplication","page":"Internal Layout and Kernels","text":"For vectors, applying the operator is conceptually:\n\nfor i in 1:N\n    left = clamp(i - HWIDTH, 1, N - WIDTH + 1)\n    ptr  = (i - 1) * WIDTH + 1\n    y[i] = sum(D.coeffs[ptr + k - 1] * x[left + k - 1]\n               for k in 1:WIDTH)\nend\n\nThe real implementation generalizes this to arrays of any rank and any differentiated dimension:\n\nmul!(y, D, x, Val(DIM))\n\nFor each fiber along DIM, it applies the same row-wise stencil. The generated kernel splits the differentiated index into three regions:\n\nhead: rows that use the left boundary stencil,\nbody: rows that use centered stencils,\ntail: rows that use the right boundary stencil.\n\nThe body is especially cheap: the input base index is i - HWIDTH, and the coefficient pointer advances by exactly WIDTH after every output. Because WIDTH is a type parameter, the inner dot product is unrolled at code generation time.","title":"Forward Matrix Multiplication"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/internals/#Why-Generated-Kernels?","page":"Internal Layout and Kernels","text":"The package uses generated functions in src/matmul.jl so that the generated loop nest knows:\n\nthe rank N of the array,\nthe differentiated dimension DIM,\nthe stencil width WIDTH.\n\nThat lets the code emit direct indexing expressions like:\n\nx[i1, i2, i3]\n\nwith only the differentiated index replaced by the stencil index. This avoids runtime construction of Cartesian indices and keeps the inner stencil loop small.\n\nFor example, differentiating a 3D array along dimension 2 conceptually emits loops of the form:\n\nfor i3 in axes(x, 3)\n    for i2 in rows_to_compute\n        for i1 in axes(x, 1)\n            y[i1, i2, i3] = stencil_dot(...)\n        end\n    end\nend\n\nThe actual generated expression also handles head/body/tail regions and decomposed-domain local ranges.","title":"Why Generated Kernels?"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/internals/#Decomposed-Domain-Pointers","page":"Internal Layout and Kernels","text":"The lower-level multiplication method:\n\nmul!(y_local, D, x_local, Val(DIM), global_idx, local_rng)\n\nuses global_idx to map local index 1 to a global matrix row. The global row computed at local index i_local is:\n\ni_mathrmglobal = mathrmglobal_idx + i_mathrmlocal - 1\n\nThe coefficient pointer for the first computed local row is therefore:\n\n(mathrmglobal_idx + i_mathrmlocal - 2)mathrmWIDTH + 1\n\nThis is why local arrays with halo points should pass global_idx for local index 1, not for first(local_rng).","title":"Decomposed-Domain Pointers"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/internals/#Adjoint-Operator-Layout","page":"Internal Layout and Kernels","text":"The transpose of a banded matrix cannot use the same simple row-major WIDTH-per-row layout near the boundaries. A column of the forward matrix may receive fewer or more nonzero contributions depending on its position.\n\nAdjointDiffMatrix therefore stores coefficients output-by-output for the adjoint action:\n\ny_j = sum_i A^*_ji x_i\n\nThe number of coefficients for adjoint output j is:\n\nj + HWIDTH in the head region,\nWIDTH in the body region,\nN - j + HWIDTH + 1 in the tail region.\n\nFor WIDTH = 5, this looks like:\n\noutput 1:  coefficients from forward rows 1:3\noutput 2:  coefficients from forward rows 1:4\noutput 3:  coefficients from forward rows 1:5\noutput 4:  coefficients from forward rows 2:6\n...\noutput N-2: coefficients from forward rows N-4:N\noutput N-1: coefficients from forward rows N-3:N\noutput N:   coefficients from forward rows N-2:N\n\nThe helper _ptr_for_j(j, N, Val(WIDTH)) returns the first coefficient for output j in this variable-length storage.","title":"Adjoint Operator Layout"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/internals/#Adjoint-Pointer-Formula","page":"Internal Layout and Kernels","text":"Let HWIDTH = WIDTH ÷ 2. The pointer has three cases:\n\nmathrmptr(j) =\nbegincases\n1 + mathrmHWIDTH(j-1) + (j-1)j2\n j le mathrmWIDTH\n(j-1)mathrmWIDTH + 1\n mathrmWIDTH  j le N-mathrmWIDTH\n(N-mathrmWIDTH)mathrmWIDTH + 1\n+ (mathrmWIDTH+mathrmHWIDTH+1)(j_t-1)\n- (j_t-1)j_t2\n j  N-mathrmWIDTH\nendcases\n\nwhere j_t = j - (N - WIDTH).\n\nThe head formula sums the growing row lengths. The body formula works because all previous body outputs have exactly WIDTH coefficients. The tail formula sums the shrinking row lengths.","title":"Adjoint Pointer Formula"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/internals/#Weighted-Adjoint-Coefficients","page":"Internal Layout and Kernels","text":"For a weighted inner product with W = Diagonal(w), the weighted adjoint is:\n\nD^+ = W^-1D^T W\n\nThe stored coefficient for adjoint output j and source row i is:\n\nD_ijfracw_iw_j\n\nThis factor is inserted once when constructing adjoint(D, w). Multiplication then uses the same adjoint kernel as the unweighted case.","title":"Weighted Adjoint Coefficients"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/internals/#Source-Code-Guide","page":"Internal Layout and Kernels","text":"The implementation is split by responsibility:\n\nsrc/utils.jl: finite-difference weights and coefficient-table assembly.\nsrc/diffmatrix.jl: compact forward matrix type and dense/indexing views.\nsrc/adjoint.jl: adjoint storage layout, pointer formulas, and construction.\nsrc/matmul.jl: generated kernels for forward and adjoint application.\nsrc/linalg.jl: reference banded routines and compact DiffMatrix solves.\nsrc/grids.jl: grid constructors and quadrature weights.\n\nWhen extending the package, keep these invariants in mind:\n\nDiffMatrix stores exactly WIDTH coefficients per row.\nWIDTH is a type parameter and must remain available to generated kernels.\nAdjointDiffMatrix stores output-major variable-length rows.\nglobal_idx always refers to local index 1 in decomposed-domain kernels.\nfull(A) and scalar indexing should agree with mul! semantics, including weighted adjoints.","title":"Source-Code Guide"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/dimension-wise/#Dimension-Wise-Differentiation","page":"Dimension-Wise Differentiation","text":"DiffMatrix is a one-dimensional operator, but it can be applied along any dimension of an array. This is often the most important feature in PDE codes: the storage layout can be chosen for cache locality, FFT planning, or domain decomposition without changing the finite-difference operator.","title":"Dimension-Wise Differentiation"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/dimension-wise/#First-Dimension","page":"Dimension-Wise Differentiation","text":"using FDGrids\nusing LinearAlgebra\n\nnx = 48\nny = 6\n\ng = grid(nx, -1, 1, GaussLobattoGrid())\nD = DiffMatrix(g.xs, 5, 1)\n\nys = range(0, 2π; length = ny)\nu  = [sin(x) * cos(y) for x in g.xs, y in ys]\nux = similar(u)\n\nmul!(ux, D, u, Val(1))\nsize(ux)\n\nEach column of u is differentiated independently along the first dimension.","title":"First Dimension"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/dimension-wise/#Second-Dimension","page":"Dimension-Wise Differentiation","text":"If the grid direction is stored along the second dimension, change only the Val argument:\n\nu2  = [sin(x) * cos(y) for y in ys, x in g.xs]\nux2 = similar(u2)\n\nmul!(ux2, D, u2, Val(2))\nsize(ux2)\n\nThe differentiated dimension must have length size(D, 1). All other dimensions are treated as batch dimensions.","title":"Second Dimension"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/dimension-wise/#Higher-Dimensional-Arrays","page":"Dimension-Wise Differentiation","text":"The same interface works for arrays with more dimensions:\n\nnz = 4\nu3 = [sin(x) * cos(y) * (1 + z)\n      for z in 1:nz, x in g.xs, y in ys]\n\nux3 = similar(u3)\nmul!(ux3, D, u3, Val(2))\n\nsize(ux3)\n\nHere the derivative is taken along the second dimension. The first and third dimensions are carried along.","title":"Higher-Dimensional Arrays"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/dimension-wise/#Generated-Kernels","page":"Dimension-Wise Differentiation","text":"The dimension-wise methods are generated for the tuple (array rank, differentiated dimension, stencil width). The generated code:\n\nwalks the array with the differentiated index in the requested position,\nuses one-sided boundary stencils where needed,\nuses centered stencils in the interior,\nunrolls the stencil dot product using the width encoded in the DiffMatrix type.\n\nFor normal local arrays, use:\n\nmul!(y, D, x, Val(DIM))\n\nFor decomposed domains, use the lower-level methods described in Decomposed Domains.","title":"Generated Kernels"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/diffmatrix/#Finite-Difference-Operators","page":"Finite-Difference Operators","text":"DiffMatrix is a compact representation of a finite-difference differentiation matrix. It behaves like an AbstractMatrix, but it stores exactly width coefficients per row rather than a dense N×N matrix.","title":"Finite-Difference Operators"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/diffmatrix/#Construction","page":"Finite-Difference Operators","text":"D = DiffMatrix(xs, width, order)\n\nxs are the grid points.\nwidth is the odd stencil width.\norder is the derivative order.\n\nThe points may be non-uniform. They must be distinct, and the ordering must match the arrays to which the operator will be applied.","title":"Construction"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/diffmatrix/#Storage-Layout","page":"Finite-Difference Operators","text":"For N = length(xs), the coefficient vector has length N * width. Row i occupies:\n\nmathrmcoeffs(i-1)mathrmwidth+1  imathrmwidth\n\nThe logical dense matrix is banded. Entries outside the stored stencil are structural zeros.\n\nBoundary rows use shifted one-sided stencils of the same width as the centered interior stencils. This uniform row width is what allows the compact generated kernels to be simple and fast.","title":"Storage Layout"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/diffmatrix/#Applying-the-Operator","page":"Finite-Difference Operators","text":"using FDGrids\nusing LinearAlgebra\n\ng = grid(32, -1, 1, GaussLobattoGrid())\nD = DiffMatrix(g.xs, 5, 1)\n\nu = sin.(g.xs)\ny = similar(u)\nmul!(y, D, u)\n\ny[1:3]\n\nFor dense comparison:\n\ny ≈ full(D) * u\n\nUse full(D) for inspection and tests. Use mul! in performance-sensitive loops.","title":"Applying the Operator"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/diffmatrix/#Arbitrary-Array-Dimensions","page":"Finite-Difference Operators","text":"mul!(y, D, x, Val(DIM)) applies the same one-dimensional operator along dimension DIM of x. See Dimension-Wise Differentiation for a full tutorial.\n\nSee the API Reference for docstrings and signatures.","title":"Arbitrary Array Dimensions"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/adjoints/#Adjoints","page":"Adjoints","text":"FDGrids.jl provides ordinary and weighted adjoints for DiffMatrix.","title":"Adjoints"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/adjoints/#Ordinary-Adjoint","page":"Adjoints","text":"Dt = adjoint(D)\n\nconstructs an AdjointDiffMatrix representing transpose(D). The adjoint operator has its own compact coefficient storage, arranged for efficient mul! application.","title":"Ordinary Adjoint"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/adjoints/#Weighted-Adjoint","page":"Adjoints","text":"Given positive weights w and W = Diagonal(w), the weighted adjoint is\n\nD^+ = W^-1 D^T W\n\nIt is constructed with:\n\nDp = adjoint(D, w)\n\nThe weights are folded into the stored coefficients, so applying Dp does not need to form or multiply by dense diagonal matrices.","title":"Weighted Adjoint"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/adjoints/#Identity","page":"Adjoints","text":"The weighted adjoint satisfies:\n\n(Du)^T W v = u^T W (D^+v)\n\nusing FDGrids\nusing LinearAlgebra\nusing Random\n\nRandom.seed!(3)\n\ng = grid(48, -1, 1, GaussLobattoGrid())\nD = DiffMatrix(g.xs, 5, 1)\n\nw  = g.ws\nW  = Diagonal(w)\nDp = adjoint(D, w)\n\nu = randn(length(g.xs))\nv = randn(length(g.xs))\n\nDu = similar(u)\nPv = similar(v)\n\nmul!(Du, D, u)\nmul!(Pv, Dp, v)\n\n(Du' * W * v) ≈ (u' * W * Pv)","title":"Identity"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/adjoints/#Structural-Unwrap","page":"Adjoints","text":"adjoint(A::AdjointDiffMatrix) returns the parent DiffMatrix object. For an ordinary adjoint this agrees with the usual double-adjoint identity. For a weighted adjoint this is a structural unwrap, not the Euclidean adjoint of the weighted operator.\n\nSee the API Reference for docstrings and signatures.","title":"Structural Unwrap"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/benchmarks/#Benchmarks","page":"Benchmarks","text":"The scripts in benchmarks/ measure the two performance-critical operations in FDGrids: linear solves and matrix–vector products.  Run them with Julia 1.11 or later; each script saves an SVG to docs/src/assets/benchmarks/.\n\n# One-time setup (from the package root)\njulia --project=benchmarks -e '\n    using Pkg\n    Pkg.develop(path=\".\")\n    Pkg.instantiate()'\n\njulia --project=benchmarks benchmarks/linsolve.jl\njulia --project=benchmarks benchmarks/matmul.jl\njulia --project=benchmarks benchmarks/adjoint.jl\n\nThe figures embed the CPU model and available RAM of the machine they were run on.","title":"Benchmarks"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/benchmarks/#Linear-solve","page":"Benchmarks","text":"Compares three solve paths on a 1D grid, sweeping over grid sizes N = 16 … 2048 and stencil widths 3, 5, 7.  Each timing is the median of 300 samples.\n\nPath Implementation\nLAPACK lu(D) → DiffMatrixLU → ldiv! via dgbtrf!/dgbtrs! (pivoted banded LU)\nFDGrids lu!(copy(D)) → @generated ldiv! (compile-time-unrolled, no pivoting)\nGeneric same in-place factorisation, dispatched through plain scalar loops\n\nThe left panel shows absolute solve time; the right panel shows the speedup of the FDGrids path over LAPACK.\n\n<img src=\"../../assets/benchmarks/linsolve_speedup.svg\"\n     alt=\"Linear solve speedup\"\n     style=\"width:100%; max-width:900px;\" />","title":"Linear solve"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/benchmarks/#Matrix–vector-product","page":"Benchmarks","text":"Benchmarks mul!(y, D, x, Val(dim)) across:\n\nArray dimensions N = 1, 2, 3, 4 (square arrays, same size along every axis)\nDifferentiation directions dim = 1 … N\nStencil widths 3, 5, 7\n\nTo reduce the influence of thermal throttling and cache-state bias, all (N, width, dim, size) combinations are shuffled into a random order and the full sweep is repeated 10 times.  The median over those 10 runs is plotted.\n\nThe x-axis shows the per-axis array size (e.g. 64² means a 64×64 array). Throughput is reported in GEl/s (giga-elements per second): total array elements divided by median wall time.  Higher is better.  Line colour encodes stencil width; line style encodes the differentiation direction.\n\n<img src=\"../../assets/benchmarks/matmul.svg\"\n     alt=\"mul! throughput\"\n     style=\"width:100%; max-width:1100px;\" />","title":"Matrix–vector product"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/benchmarks/#Forward-vs-adjoint","page":"Benchmarks","text":"Measures the speedup of mul!(y, adjoint(D), x, Val(dim)) relative to the forward mul!(y, D, x, Val(dim)), defined as forward time / adjoint time. A value above 1 means the adjoint is faster; below 1 it carries overhead. A dashed line at 1 marks parity.\n\nThe same array dimensions, stencil widths, and size ranges as the matrix–vector product benchmark are used, with the same randomised 10-pass median methodology. Colour encodes stencil width; line style encodes differentiation direction.\n\n<img src=\"../../assets/benchmarks/adjoint.svg\"\n     alt=\"Adjoint speedup over forward\"\n     style=\"width:100%; max-width:1100px;\" />","title":"Forward vs adjoint"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/grids/#Grids-and-Quadrature","page":"Grids and Quadrature","text":"The grid API constructs points and quadrature weights together:\n\ng = grid(M, l, h, distribution)\n\nThe return value is a named tuple with fields xs and ws. The points are in ascending order and the weights approximate integrals on [l,h]:\n\nint_l^h f(x)dx approx sum_i f(x_i) w_i","title":"Grids and Quadrature"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/grids/#Available-Distributions","page":"Grids and Quadrature","text":"","title":"Available Distributions"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/grids/#[UniformGrid](@ref)","page":"Grids and Quadrature","text":"UniformGrid() places equally spaced points on [l,h]. Its weights are the composite trapezoidal rule: half weights at the endpoints and full cell widths in the interior.","title":"UniformGrid"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/grids/#[MappedGrid](@ref)","page":"Grids and Quadrature","text":"MappedGrid(α, order) places mapped Chebyshev-like points:\n\nx_j =\nfracsin^-1(-alpha cos(pi j(M-1)))sin^-1(alpha)\nfrach-l2\n+ frach+l2\nqquad j = 0ldotsM-1\n\nThe clustering parameter satisfies 0 < α ≤ 1. Smaller α gives stronger endpoint clustering; α = 1 gives uniform spacing. Quadrature weights are computed with composite Newton-Cotes panels of degree order.\n\nHigh-order Newton-Cotes rules on strongly non-uniform nodes may produce negative weights. If a positive definite weighted inner product is required, prefer GaussLobattoGrid().","title":"MappedGrid"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/grids/#[GaussLobattoGrid](@ref)","page":"Grids and Quadrature","text":"GaussLobattoGrid() uses Chebyshev-Lobatto points:\n\nx_j = fracl+h2\n    + frach-l2cosleft(fracpi(M-1-j)M-1right)\nqquad j = 0ldotsM-1\n\nThe associated quadrature is Clenshaw-Curtis quadrature, with positive weights for the grids supported by this package. This is often the best default for weighted adjoints.","title":"GaussLobattoGrid"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/grids/#Examples","page":"Grids and Quadrature","text":"using FDGrids\n\ng = grid(64, -1, 1, GaussLobattoGrid())\nsum(exp.(g.xs) .* g.ws)\n\ng = grid(64, -1, 1, UniformGrid())\nall(g.ws .> 0)\n\nSee the API Reference for docstrings and signatures.","title":"Examples"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/decomposed-domains/#Decomposed-Domains","page":"Decomposed Domains","text":"The ordinary dimension-wise interface\n\nmul!(y, D, x, Val(DIM))\n\nassumes that x and y contain the full differentiated dimension. For distributed arrays or slab-local storage, FDGrids.jl also provides a lower level interface:\n\nmul!(y_local, D, x_local, Val(DIM), global_idx, local_rng)\n\nThis applies the global operator D to a local array.","title":"Decomposed Domains"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/decomposed-domains/#Arguments","page":"Decomposed Domains","text":"DIM is the local array dimension being differentiated.\nglobal_idx is the global row index corresponding to local index 1.\nlocal_rng selects the local rows to compute along dimension DIM.\n\nThe method does not communicate halo values. A domain-decomposition layer must ensure that x_local contains all values required by the stencils in local_rng.","title":"Arguments"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/decomposed-domains/#Slab-with-Halo-Points","page":"Decomposed Domains","text":"Suppose the global differentiated direction has length 64, the stencil width is 5, and a rank owns global rows 17:32. A centered width-5 stencil needs two neighboring values on either side, so the local storage includes rows 15:34.\n\nusing FDGrids\nusing LinearAlgebra\nusing Random\n\nRandom.seed!(2)\n\nnx = 64\nny = 8\n\ng = grid(nx, -1, 1, GaussLobattoGrid())\nD = DiffMatrix(g.xs, 5, 1)\n\nowned  = 17:32\nstored = 15:34\nlocal_owned = (first(owned) - first(stored) + 1):(last(owned) - first(stored) + 1)\n\nx_local = randn(length(stored), ny)\ny_local = similar(x_local)\n\nmul!(y_local, D, x_local, Val(1), first(stored), local_owned)\n\nsize(y_local)\n\nOnly the rows in local_owned are meaningful outputs from this call. The halo rows in y_local are just storage.","title":"Slab with Halo Points"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/decomposed-domains/#Decomposed-Direction-on-Another-Axis","page":"Decomposed Domains","text":"The decomposed direction does not need to be the first local array dimension:\n\nx_local_2 = randn(ny, length(stored))\ny_local_2 = similar(x_local_2)\n\nmul!(y_local_2, D, x_local_2, Val(2), first(stored), local_owned)\n\nsize(y_local_2)\n\nThis is the same global operation, but with the differentiated index stored along local dimension 2.","title":"Decomposed Direction on Another Axis"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/decomposed-domains/#Boundary-Workflows","page":"Decomposed Domains","text":"If a local array does not contain enough halo values, restrict local_rng to the rows whose stencil support is local. Boundary or overlap rows can then be filled by another communication/computation step.\n\nThe interface deliberately leaves communication policy outside FDGrids.jl. That keeps the finite-difference kernels reusable across threaded, MPI, GPU, or custom slab-storage implementations.","title":"Boundary Workflows"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/getting-started/#Getting-Started","page":"Getting Started","text":"This tutorial builds a finite-difference operator on a non-uniform grid and applies it to a vector.","title":"Getting Started"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/getting-started/#Build-a-Grid","page":"Getting Started","text":"The main grid API returns points and quadrature weights together:\n\nusing FDGrids\nusing LinearAlgebra\n\ng = grid(32, -1, 1, GaussLobattoGrid())\n(length(g.xs), length(g.ws), first(g.xs), last(g.xs))\n\ng.xs contains grid points in ascending order and g.ws contains quadrature weights associated with those points.","title":"Build a Grid"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/getting-started/#Construct-a-Differentiation-Matrix","page":"Getting Started","text":"DiffMatrix(xs, width, order) constructs a derivative operator on the nodes xs. The stencil width must be odd.\n\nD = DiffMatrix(g.xs, 5, 1)\nsize(D)\n\nThis is a first-derivative operator with a five-point stencil. On interior rows the stencil is centered; near the boundaries it is shifted to use one-sided stencils of the same width.","title":"Construct a Differentiation Matrix"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/getting-started/#Apply-the-Operator","page":"Getting Started","text":"Use mul! for repeated application:\n\nu  = sin.(g.xs)\ndu = similar(u)\n\nmul!(du, D, u)\ndu[1:4]\n\nFor inspection, testing, or comparison with dense linear algebra, expand the compact operator:\n\nDf = full(D)\ndu ≈ Df * u","title":"Apply the Operator"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/getting-started/#Choose-a-Wider-Stencil","page":"Getting Started","text":"The same grid can be used with different derivative orders and stencil widths:\n\nD2 = DiffMatrix(g.xs, 7, 2)   # second derivative, 7-point stencil\nd2u = similar(u)\nmul!(d2u, D2, u)\n\nd2u[1:4]\n\nWider stencils use more points per row and can improve accuracy for smooth functions, but they also increase the bandwidth of the operator and the amount of halo data needed in decomposed-domain applications.","title":"Choose a Wider Stencil"},{"category":"section","location":"api/#API-Reference","page":"API Reference","text":"This page collects the public API. Deprecated compatibility functions are listed separately in Deprecated API.","title":"API Reference"},{"category":"section","location":"api/#Grids","page":"API Reference","text":"","title":"Grids"},{"category":"section","location":"api/#Finite-Difference-Matrices","page":"API Reference","text":"","title":"Finite-Difference Matrices"},{"category":"section","location":"api/#Multiplication","page":"API Reference","text":"","title":"Multiplication"},{"category":"section","location":"api/#Adjoints","page":"API Reference","text":"","title":"Adjoints"},{"category":"section","location":"api/#Linear-Solves","page":"API Reference","text":"","title":"Linear Solves"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#FDGrids.AbstractGridDistribution","page":"API Reference","text":"AbstractGridDistribution\n\nAbstract supertype for all grid distributions. Concrete subtypes dispatch the grid function to the appropriate node-placement and quadrature algorithm, always returning nodes and weights together so they are guaranteed to be consistent.\n\nType Nodes Endpoints Quadrature Always positive weights?\nMappedGrid(α, order) Mapped Chebyshev yes Composite Newton-Cotes not guaranteed\nUniformGrid() Equally spaced yes Composite trapezoidal yes\nGaussLobattoGrid() Chebyshev-Lobatto yes Clenshaw-Curtis yes\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"FDGrids.AbstractGridDistribution"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#FDGrids.MappedGrid","page":"API Reference","text":"MappedGrid(α=0.5, order=2)\n\nMapped Chebyshev grid with clustering parameter α ∈ (0,1]. Nodes are placed at\n\nxⱼ = asin(-α cos(πj/(M-1))) / asin(α) · (h-l)/2 + (h+l)/2,    j = 0, …, M-1\n\nα=1 gives uniform spacing; α→0 approaches the Chebyshev-Lobatto distribution.\n\norder is the polynomial degree of the composite Newton-Cotes quadrature rule. Positive weights are not guaranteed for high order or strongly non-uniform nodes. The default is order=2, i.e. Simpson panels. Other typical values are 1 (trapezoidal), 3, and 4.\n\nExamples\n\ng = grid(48, -1, 1, MappedGrid(0.5, 4))\nsum(exp.(g.xs) .* g.ws)\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"FDGrids.MappedGrid"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#FDGrids.UniformGrid","page":"API Reference","text":"UniformGrid()\n\nEqually-spaced grid. The associated quadrature is the composite trapezoidal rule, which always produces strictly positive weights.\n\nExamples\n\ng = grid(16, 0, 1, UniformGrid())\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"FDGrids.UniformGrid"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#FDGrids.GaussLobattoGrid","page":"API Reference","text":"GaussLobattoGrid()\n\nChebyshev-Lobatto (Gauss-Lobatto) grid: M nodes at\n\nxⱼ = (l+h)/2 + (h-l)/2 · cos(π(M-1-j)/(M-1)),    j = 0, …, M-1\n\nincluding both endpoints, clustered near the boundaries.\n\nThe associated quadrature is Clenshaw-Curtis, which has strictly positive weights and is spectrally accurate for smooth integrands.\n\nThis is the recommended distribution when a positive-definite inner product is required (e.g. for adjoint(D, w)). Fields with zero boundary conditions produce zero endpoint contributions regardless of the endpoint weights, so Gauss-Lobatto is equally suitable for zero-BC problems while supporting the standard BC-enforcement pattern of overwriting rows 1 and M of D.\n\nExamples\n\ng = grid(32, -1, 1, GaussLobattoGrid())\nD = DiffMatrix(g.xs, 5, 1)\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"FDGrids.GaussLobattoGrid"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#FDGrids.grid","page":"API Reference","text":"grid(M, l=-1.0, h=1.0, dist=MappedGrid(0.5)) -> (xs::Vector, ws::Vector)\n\nCompute M grid points and their associated quadrature weights on [l, h] according to the distribution dist. Points and weights are always computed together, ensuring they are guaranteed to be consistent.\n\nArguments\n\nM: Number of grid points. Must be ≥ 2.\nl, h: Left and right endpoints; must satisfy l < h.\ndist: An AbstractGridDistribution. Defaults to MappedGrid(0.5).\n\nReturns\n\nA named tuple (xs = points, ws = weights) where:\n\nxs[i] is the i-th grid point in ascending order.\nws[i] is the quadrature weight at xs[i], so that sum(f.(xs) .* ws) approximates ∫_l^h f(x) dx.\n\nExamples\n\ng = grid(64, -1, 1, GaussLobattoGrid())  # Clenshaw-Curtis, always positive\nsum(exp.(g.xs) .* g.ws)\n\nxs, ws = grid(64, -1, 1, UniformGrid())  # named tuples can be destructured\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"FDGrids.grid"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#FDGrids.DiffMatrix","page":"API Reference","text":"DiffMatrix{T, WIDTH, OPTIMISE} <: AbstractMatrix{T}\n\nCompact representation of a banded NxN  finite-difference differentiation matrix with stencil width WIDTH.\n\nCoefficients are stored in a flat vector coeffs of length N*WIDTH: for output row i, the WIDTH stencil weights occupy coeffs[(i-1)*WIDTH+1 : i*WIDTH].\n\nOPTIMISE controls whether the diagonal of the LU factor U is stored inverted (saves one division per element in the triangular solve).\n\nExamples\n\nusing LinearAlgebra\n\nxs = range(-1, 1; length = 64)\nD  = DiffMatrix(xs, 5, 1)   # first derivative, 5-point stencil\n\nu  = sin.(xs)\ndu = similar(u)\nmul!(du, D, u)\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"FDGrids.DiffMatrix"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#FDGrids.full","page":"API Reference","text":"full(A::DiffMatrix) -> Matrix{T}\n\nExpand the compact stencil representation into a dense N×N matrix.\n\nThis is mainly intended for inspection, testing, and comparison with dense linear algebra. Applying a DiffMatrix with mul! uses the compact stencil storage directly and avoids building this dense matrix.\n\nExamples\n\nxs = range(-1, 1; length = 8)\nD  = DiffMatrix(xs, 3, 1)\nM  = full(D)\n\n\n\n\n\nfull(A::AdjointDiffMatrix) -> Matrix{T}\n\nExpand the adjoint operator into a dense N×N matrix.\n\nFor weighted adjoints, this expands the weighted operator represented by A.coeffs, not merely the unweighted transpose of the parent matrix.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"FDGrids.full"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#FDGrids.basis_vector","page":"API Reference","text":"basis_vector(i, P, [T=Float64]) -> Vector{T}\n\nReturn the i-th canonical basis vector of length P with element type T.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"FDGrids.basis_vector"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#LinearAlgebra.mul!-Union{Tuple{DIM}, Tuple{WIDTH}, Tuple{N}, Tuple{S}, Tuple{T}, Tuple{AbstractArray{S, N}, DiffMatrix{T, WIDTH}, AbstractArray{S, N}, Val{DIM}}} where {T, S, N, WIDTH, DIM}","page":"API Reference","text":"LinearAlgebra.mul!(y, A::DiffMatrix, x, ::Val{DIM}=Val(1)) -> y\n\nApply the forward finite-difference operator A to x along dimension DIM, writing the result into y. Non-distributed entry point.\n\nFor vectors, the default DIM=1 applies the usual matrix-vector action. For higher-dimensional arrays, each one-dimensional fiber along DIM is differentiated independently.\n\nExamples\n\nusing LinearAlgebra\n\nxs = range(-1, 1; length = 32)\nD  = DiffMatrix(xs, 5, 1)\n\nu  = sin.(xs)\ndu = similar(u)\nmul!(du, D, u)\n\nA  = repeat(reshape(u, :, 1), 1, 4)\ndA = similar(A)\nmul!(dA, D, A, Val(1))\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"LinearAlgebra.mul!"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#LinearAlgebra.mul!-Union{Tuple{DIM}, Tuple{WIDTH}, Tuple{N}, Tuple{TD}, Tuple{T}, Tuple{AbstractArray{T, N}, DiffMatrix{TD, WIDTH}, AbstractArray{T, N}, Val{DIM}, Int64, UnitRange}} where {T, TD, N, WIDTH, DIM}","page":"API Reference","text":"LinearAlgebra.mul!(y, A::DiffMatrix, x, ::Val{DIM}, global_idx, local_rng) -> y\n\nDistribution-aware backend for the forward operator. @generated for the concrete (T, N, WIDTH, DIM) combination.\n\nglobal_idx: global row index corresponding to local index 1 of x/y.\nlocal_rng: local portion of dimension DIM to process.\n\nThis method is intended for domain-decomposed callers. Ordinary local arrays should use mul!(y, A, x, Val(DIM)).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"LinearAlgebra.mul!"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#LinearAlgebra.mul!-Union{Tuple{WIDTH}, Tuple{T}, Tuple{DiffMatrix{T, WIDTH}, AbstractVector, Int64}} where {T, WIDTH}","page":"API Reference","text":"LinearAlgebra.mul!(A::DiffMatrix{T, WIDTH}, x::AbstractVector, i::Int)\n\nEvaluate row i of the forward operator A applied to x. The sum is unrolled at generation time.\n\nThis is useful when only one differentiated value is needed. It does not mutate A or x.\n\nExamples\n\nusing LinearAlgebra\n\nxs = range(-1, 1; length = 16)\nD  = DiffMatrix(xs, 5, 1)\ndu_at_3 = mul!(D, sin.(xs), 3)\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"LinearAlgebra.mul!"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#FDGrids.AdjointDiffMatrix","page":"API Reference","text":"AdjointDiffMatrix{T, WIDTH} <: AbstractMatrix{T}\n\nTransposed finite-difference differentiation matrix D*, constructed from a DiffMatrix by adjoint(D).\n\nadjoint(D, w) constructs the adjoint under the weighted inner product with diagonal weights w, representing W^-1 * transpose(D) * W.\n\nThe parent DiffMatrix is retained so adjoint(A::AdjointDiffMatrix) can return the original operator without copying. For weighted adjoints this is a structural unwrap, not the standard Euclidean adjoint of the weighted operator.\n\nCoefficients for the transpose operator are stored in a single flat vector coeffs of length N*WIDTH. For each output j (1..N), the contributing input rows are stored consecutively:\n\nhead j ∈ 1:WIDTH        → j+HWIDTH entries, inputs 1..j+HWIDTH\nbody j ∈ WIDTH+1:N-WIDTH → WIDTH entries,  inputs j-HWIDTH..j+HWIDTH\ntail j ∈ N-WIDTH+1:N    → N-j+HWIDTH+1 entries, inputs j-HWIDTH..N\n\nThe pointer for any output j is given in closed form by _ptr_for_j.\n\nExamples\n\nusing LinearAlgebra\n\nxs = range(-1, 1; length = 16)\nD  = DiffMatrix(xs, 5, 1)\nDt = adjoint(D)\n\ny = similar(collect(xs))\nmul!(y, Dt, sin.(xs))\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"FDGrids.AdjointDiffMatrix"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#Base.adjoint-Tuple{DiffMatrix}","page":"API Reference","text":"adjoint(D::DiffMatrix) -> AdjointDiffMatrix\n\nConstruct the transposed differentiation matrix D*.\n\nBuilds coeffs (length NWIDTH) once at O(NWIDTH) cost; all subsequent mul! calls are allocation-free. Requires size(D,1) > 2*WIDTH.\n\nExamples\n\nusing LinearAlgebra\n\nxs = range(-1, 1; length = 16)\nD  = DiffMatrix(xs, 5, 1)\nDt = adjoint(D)\n\n\n\n\n\nadjoint(D::DiffMatrix, w) -> AdjointDiffMatrix\n\nConstruct the adjoint of D under the weighted inner product (u,v)_W = u'Wv where W = Diagonal(w). The result represents D⁺ = W⁻¹ D* W.\n\nWeights are fused into coeffs at construction time: the stored entry for adjoint row j and source row i is D[i,j] * w[i] / w[j]. Requires size(D,1) > 2*WIDTH.\n\nExamples\n\nusing LinearAlgebra\n\ng  = grid(32, -1, 1, GaussLobattoGrid())\nD  = DiffMatrix(g.xs, 5, 1)\nDt = adjoint(D, g.ws)\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Base.adjoint"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#Base.adjoint-Union{Tuple{WIDTH}, Tuple{T}, Tuple{DiffMatrix{T, WIDTH}, AbstractVector{T}}} where {T, WIDTH}","page":"API Reference","text":"adjoint(D::DiffMatrix, w) -> AdjointDiffMatrix\n\nConstruct the adjoint of D under the weighted inner product (u,v)_W = u'Wv where W = Diagonal(w). The result represents D⁺ = W⁻¹ D* W.\n\nWeights are fused into coeffs at construction time: the stored entry for adjoint row j and source row i is D[i,j] * w[i] / w[j]. Requires size(D,1) > 2*WIDTH.\n\nExamples\n\nusing LinearAlgebra\n\ng  = grid(32, -1, 1, GaussLobattoGrid())\nD  = DiffMatrix(g.xs, 5, 1)\nDt = adjoint(D, g.ws)\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Base.adjoint"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#Base.adjoint-Tuple{AdjointDiffMatrix}","page":"API Reference","text":"adjoint(D::AdjointDiffMatrix) -> DiffMatrix\n\nReturn the parent forward matrix. No copy is made.\n\nThis is a structural operation: AdjointDiffMatrix stores a reference to the DiffMatrix from which it was constructed, and this method returns that object. For an unweighted adjoint this agrees with taking the adjoint twice. For a weighted adjoint built by adjoint(D, w), this does not mean that the standard Euclidean adjoint of W^-1 * transpose(D) * W is D; the weights are not stored separately, and this method intentionally discards the weighted operator view.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"Base.adjoint"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#LinearAlgebra.mul!-Union{Tuple{DIM}, Tuple{WIDTH}, Tuple{N}, Tuple{S}, Tuple{T}, Tuple{AbstractArray{S, N}, AdjointDiffMatrix{T, WIDTH}, AbstractArray{S, N}, Val{DIM}}} where {T, S, N, WIDTH, DIM}","page":"API Reference","text":"LinearAlgebra.mul!(y, A::AdjointDiffMatrix, x, ::Val{DIM}=Val(1)) -> y\n\nApply the transposed finite-difference operator A = D* to x along dimension DIM, writing the result into y. Non-distributed entry point.\n\nExamples\n\nusing LinearAlgebra\n\nxs = range(-1, 1; length = 32)\nD  = DiffMatrix(xs, 5, 1)\nDt = adjoint(D)\n\ny = similar(collect(xs))\nmul!(y, Dt, cos.(xs))\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"LinearAlgebra.mul!"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#LinearAlgebra.mul!-Union{Tuple{DIM}, Tuple{WIDTH}, Tuple{N}, Tuple{TD}, Tuple{T}, Tuple{AbstractArray{T, N}, AdjointDiffMatrix{TD, WIDTH}, AbstractArray{T, N}, Val{DIM}, Int64, UnitRange}} where {T, TD, N, WIDTH, DIM}","page":"API Reference","text":"LinearAlgebra.mul!(y, A::AdjointDiffMatrix, x, ::Val{DIM}, global_idx, local_rng) -> y\n\nDistribution-aware backend for the adjoint operator. @generated for the concrete (T, N, WIDTH, DIM) combination.\n\nglobal_idx: global row index corresponding to local index 1 of x/y.\nlocal_rng: local portion of dimension DIM to process.\n\nThis method is intended for distributed or slab-local application of an adjoint operator. Ordinary local arrays should use mul!(y, A, x, Val(DIM)).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"LinearAlgebra.mul!"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#LinearAlgebra.lu-Tuple{DiffMatrix}","page":"API Reference","text":"lu(D::DiffMatrix) -> DiffMatrixLU\n\nCompute a pivoted banded LU factorisation of D using LAPACK.\n\nThis is the allocating, LAPACK-backed factorisation path. It preserves the compact DiffMatrix input and stores the factors in LAPACK banded format.\n\nUse this when comparing against LAPACK or when pivoting is desired. For performance-critical repeated solves with DiffMatrix, prefer the compact in-place path lu!(copy(D)) followed by ldiv!(factorised_D, rhs).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"LinearAlgebra.lu"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#LinearAlgebra.ldiv!-Union{Tuple{WIDTH}, Tuple{T}, Tuple{FDGrids.DiffMatrixLU{T, WIDTH}, AbstractVector{T}}} where {T, WIDTH}","page":"API Reference","text":"ldiv!(lu::DiffMatrixLU, x) -> x\n\nSolve the linear system represented by a DiffMatrixLU factorisation in place.\n\nx is overwritten with the solution. The factorisation must have been produced by lu(D) for a compatible DiffMatrix.\n\nThis solves through LAPACK's banded storage and is mainly a reference/comparison path for the compact generated implementation below.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"LinearAlgebra.ldiv!"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#LinearAlgebra.lu!-Tuple{DiffMatrix}","page":"API Reference","text":"lu!(A::DiffMatrix) -> A\n\nFactor a DiffMatrix in place with the no-pivoting banded LU routine.\n\nThe factorisation overwrites the compact coefficients of A. If the OPTIMISE type parameter is true, the diagonal of U is inverted during factorisation to save divisions during repeated triangular solves.\n\nThis is the preferred factorisation path for performance-critical code using DiffMatrix. It avoids LAPACK workspace conversion and keeps the factors in the same compact coefficient storage. Copy the matrix first if the original differentiation operator is still needed.\n\nExamples\n\nDfac = lu!(copy(D))\nldiv!(Dfac, rhs)\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"LinearAlgebra.lu!"},{"category":"method","location":"api/#LinearAlgebra.ldiv!-Tuple{DiffMatrix, AbstractVector}","page":"API Reference","text":"ldiv!(A::DiffMatrix, b) -> b\n\nSolve in place using a DiffMatrix that has already been factorised by lu!.\n\nThis dispatch uses generated triangular solves specialised on the stencil width encoded in the DiffMatrix type. It is the preferred performance-critical solve path in this file.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"LinearAlgebra.ldiv!"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#FDGrids.banded_lu!","page":"API Reference","text":"banded_lu!(A, p, q; optimise=false) -> A\n\nPublic wrapper around the generic reference banded LU factorisation.\n\np is the number of subdiagonals and q is the number of superdiagonals. The matrix A is overwritten with the no-pivot LU factors produced by the reference implementation _banded_lu!.\n\nThis routine is intended for reference and experimentation with ordinary matrices. Performance-critical code using DiffMatrix should prefer lu!(copy(D)) and ldiv!(Dfac, rhs).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"FDGrids.banded_lu!"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#FDGrids.banded_tril_solve!","page":"API Reference","text":"banded_tril_solve!(L, b, p) -> b\n\nPublic wrapper around the generic reference forward-substitution routine.\n\nL is assumed to contain the unit-lower triangular factor produced by banded_lu!, and only the first p subdiagonals are inspected. The vector b is overwritten.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"FDGrids.banded_tril_solve!"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#FDGrids.banded_triu_solve","page":"API Reference","text":"banded_triu_solve(U, b, q) -> b\n\nPublic wrapper around the generic reference back-substitution routine.\n\nU is assumed to contain the upper triangular factor produced by banded_lu!, and only the first q superdiagonals are inspected. The vector b is overwritten.\n\nThis exported name is kept for compatibility with the existing public API even though the function mutates b.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"FDGrids.banded_triu_solve"},{"category":"section","location":"deprecated/#Deprecated-API","page":"Deprecated API","text":"These functions are retained for compatibility with older FDGrids.jl code. New code should use grid, DiffMatrix, and the standard LinearAlgebra methods documented in the main API Reference.","title":"Deprecated API"},{"category":"section","location":"deprecated/#Grid-Points","page":"Deprecated API","text":"gridpoints returns only grid points. Prefer grid(...).xs, which keeps points and weights paired.","title":"Grid Points"},{"category":"section","location":"deprecated/#Quadrature-Weights","page":"Deprecated API","text":"quadweights and _quadweights are older quadrature entry points. Prefer grid(...).ws, because the weight rule should match the grid distribution.","title":"Quadrature Weights"},{"category":"function","location":"deprecated/#FDGrids.gridpoints","page":"Deprecated API","text":"gridpoints(M, l=-1.0, h=1.0, α=0.5) -> Vector\n\nReturn grid points only. Preserved for backward compatibility.\n\nDeprecated: use grid(M, l, h, MappedGrid(α)).xs instead. Use grid directly when both points and quadrature weights are needed.\n\nExamples\n\nxs = grid(32, -1, 1, MappedGrid(0.5)).xs\n\n\n\n\n\ngridpoints(M, l, h, dist::AbstractGridDistribution) -> Vector\n\nReturn grid points only for the given distribution.\n\nDeprecated: use grid(M, l, h, dist).xs instead. Use grid directly when both points and quadrature weights are needed.\n\nExamples\n\nxs = grid(32, -1, 1, GaussLobattoGrid()).xs\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"FDGrids.gridpoints"},{"category":"function","location":"deprecated/#FDGrids.quadweights","page":"Deprecated API","text":"quadweights(xs::AbstractVector, order::Int) -> Vector{Float64}\n\nComposite Newton-Cotes quadrature weights for arbitrary node positions xs, using panels of order+1 points exact for polynomials of degree order.\n\nWeights may be negative for high order or non-uniform xs. For new code, prefer grid(M, l, h, dist).ws, or use grid(M, l, h, dist) directly when both points and weights are needed.\n\nDeprecated: use grid(M, l, h, dist).ws instead.\n\nArguments\n\nxs: Mesh points. Need not be sorted; decreasing inputs are handled internally.\norder: Polynomial degree of the local rule (1 = trapezoidal, 2 = Simpson, …).\n\nExamples\n\ng  = grid(32, -1, 1, MappedGrid(0.5, 4))\nws = g.ws\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"FDGrids.quadweights"},{"category":"function","location":"deprecated/#FDGrids._quadweights","page":"Deprecated API","text":"_quadweights(xs::AbstractVector) -> Vector{Float64}\n\nExact quadrature weights for a single panel of nodes xs by solving the Vandermonde system for monomial exactness up to degree length(xs)-1:\n\nA w = b,    A[d+1, i] = xs[i]^d,    b[d+1] = (xs[end]^{d+1} - xs[1]^{d+1}) / (d+1)\n\nFor two nodes returns the trapezoidal weights [h, h]/2. For three equally-spaced nodes returns Simpson weights [1, 4, 1]*h/3.\n\nWeights may be negative for large or non-uniform panels.\n\nDeprecated: use grid(M, l, h, dist).ws for quadrature weights associated with a supported grid distribution.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"FDGrids._quadweights"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/methods/#Numerical-Methods","page":"Numerical Methods","text":"This page gives the mathematical background behind the main algorithms in FDGrids.jl.","title":"Numerical Methods"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/methods/#Finite-Difference-Weights","page":"Numerical Methods","text":"Finite-difference weights are computed with Fornberg's recursive algorithm for arbitrarily spaced nodes. Given nodes\n\nx_0 x_1 ldots x_n\n\nand an evaluation point ξ, the algorithm computes weights c_{j,k} such that\n\nf^(k)(xi) approx sum_j=0^n c_jk f(x_j)\nqquad k = 0ldotsm\n\nThis is the reason DiffMatrix can support non-uniform grids and arbitrary odd stencil widths.\n\nThe implementation in utils.jl follows the Fornberg recursion and is adapted from Marc Avila's nscouette code lineage, with Julia indexing and storage conventions.","title":"Finite-Difference Weights"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/methods/#Stencils-and-Boundary-Rows","page":"Numerical Methods","text":"For each grid point xs[i], FDGrids.jl chooses a stencil of the requested width:\n\ncentered in the interior,\nshifted to the left boundary near the first point,\nshifted to the right boundary near the last point.\n\nEvery row stores the same number of coefficients. This uniform layout is important for the generated kernels.","title":"Stencils and Boundary Rows"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/methods/#Dimension-Wise-Application","page":"Numerical Methods","text":"The generated mul! kernels apply the same one-dimensional matrix to every fiber along a selected dimension:\n\nyldots i ldots\n=\nsum_j D_ij xldots j ldots\n\nThe generated code specializes on:\n\nthe rank of the input array,\nthe differentiated dimension,\nthe stencil width.\n\nThis lets the stencil dot product be unrolled while preserving the caller's chosen memory layout.","title":"Dimension-Wise Application"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/methods/#Quadrature","page":"Numerical Methods","text":"grid returns quadrature weights with the nodes:\n\nint_l^h f(x)dx approx sum_i f(x_i)w_i\n\nThe available rules are:\n\ncomposite trapezoidal for UniformGrid,\ncomposite Newton-Cotes for MappedGrid,\nClenshaw-Curtis for GaussLobattoGrid.\n\nClenshaw-Curtis quadrature is constructed with the explicit formula described by Waldvogel.","title":"Quadrature"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/methods/#Adjoints","page":"Numerical Methods","text":"The ordinary adjoint represents D^T. The weighted adjoint represents\n\nD^+ = W^-1D^T W\n\nwhere W = Diagonal(w). The weighted coefficients are precomputed once at construction time.","title":"Adjoints"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/methods/#Linear-Solves","page":"Numerical Methods","text":"The compact in-place LU factorisation uses a no-pivoting banded algorithm. Generated triangular solves specialize on the stencil width stored in the DiffMatrix type. LAPACK wrappers are available for reference and comparison, but the compact path avoids converting to LAPACK banded workspace.","title":"Linear Solves"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/methods/#References","page":"Numerical Methods","text":"B. Fornberg, \"Generation of Finite Difference Formulas on Arbitrarily Spaced Grids\", Mathematics of Computation, 51(184), 699-706, 1988.\nB. Fornberg, A Practical Guide to Pseudospectral Methods, Cambridge University Press, 1998.\nJ. M. López, D. Feldmann, M. Rampp, A. Vela-Martín, L. Shi, and M. Avila, \"nsCouette: A High-Performance Code for Direct Numerical Simulations of Turbulent Taylor-Couette Flow\", SoftwareX, 11, 100395, 2020.\nJ. Waldvogel, \"Fast Construction of the Fejér and Clenshaw-Curtis Quadrature Rules\", BIT Numerical Mathematics, 46, 195-202, 2006.\nG. H. Golub and C. F. Van Loan, Matrix Computations, 4th edition, Johns Hopkins University Press, 2013.","title":"References"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/linear-solves/#Linear-Solves","page":"Linear Solves","text":"DiffMatrix supports banded LU factorisation and triangular solves. The file src/linalg.jl contains three layers:\n\nLAPACK banded wrappers, useful for reference and comparison.\nGeneric dense-matrix banded routines, useful as algorithmic references.\nCompact generated DiffMatrix routines, intended for performance-critical repeated solves.","title":"Linear Solves"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/linear-solves/#Compact-Path","page":"Linear Solves","text":"For performance-sensitive code, copy and factor the compact matrix in place:\n\nusing FDGrids\nusing LinearAlgebra\nusing Random\n\nRandom.seed!(4)\n\ng = grid(32, -1, 1, GaussLobattoGrid())\nD = DiffMatrix(g.xs, 5, 2)\n\nDfac = lu!(copy(D))\nrhs  = randn(size(D, 1))\n\nldiv!(Dfac, rhs)\nrhs[1:3]\n\nThe factorisation overwrites the compact coefficient storage. Use copy(D) if the original differentiation operator is still needed.","title":"Compact Path"},{"category":"section","location":"manual/linear-solves/#Reference-Paths","page":"Linear Solves","text":"The allocating LAPACK path is available via:\n\nF = lu(D)\nldiv!(F, rhs)\n\nThe generic banded reference wrappers are:\n\nbanded_lu!(A, p, q)\nbanded_tril_solve!(A, b, p)\nbanded_triu_solve(A, b, q)\n\nThese operate on ordinary matrix indexing and are useful for experiments and validation. They are not the preferred path for repeated DiffMatrix solves.\n\nSee the API Reference for docstrings and signatures.","title":"Reference Paths"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/weighted-adjoints/#Weighted-Adjoints","page":"Weighted Adjoints","text":"Finite-difference operators are often used with quadrature weights. If W = Diagonal(w), the weighted adjoint of a matrix D is the operator D⁺ that satisfies\n\n(Du)^T W v = u^T W (D^+ v)\n\nEquivalently,\n\nD^+ = W^-1 D^T W\n\nFDGrids.jl constructs this operator without explicitly forming the dense diagonal matrices.","title":"Weighted Adjoints"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/weighted-adjoints/#Verify-the-Identity","page":"Weighted Adjoints","text":"using FDGrids\nusing LinearAlgebra\nusing Random\n\nRandom.seed!(1)\n\ng = grid(48, -1, 1, GaussLobattoGrid())\nD = DiffMatrix(g.xs, 5, 1)\n\nw  = g.ws\nW  = Diagonal(w)\nDp = adjoint(D, w)\n\nu = randn(length(g.xs))\nv = randn(length(g.xs))\n\nDu  = similar(u)\nDpv = similar(v)\n\nmul!(Du, D, u)\nmul!(Dpv, Dp, v)\n\nleft  = Du' * W * v\nright = u'  * W * Dpv\n\nleft ≈ right\n\nThe weighted adjoint stores the factors w[i] / w[j] inside its coefficient array. This keeps subsequent mul! calls allocation-free and avoids applying W and W^{-1} every time.","title":"Verify the Identity"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/weighted-adjoints/#Dense-Comparison","page":"Weighted Adjoints","text":"For testing and debugging, compare against the dense expression:\n\nDp_dense = Diagonal(1 ./ w) * full(D)' * Diagonal(w)\nfull(Dp) ≈ Dp_dense","title":"Dense Comparison"},{"category":"section","location":"tutorials/weighted-adjoints/#Structural-Double-Adjoint","page":"Weighted Adjoints","text":"adjoint(A::AdjointDiffMatrix) returns the parent DiffMatrix object:\n\nadjoint(Dp) === D\n\nFor an unweighted adjoint this matches the usual double-adjoint intuition. For a weighted adjoint it is a structural unwrap of the original operator, not the Euclidean adjoint of W^{-1} D^T W.","title":"Structural Double-Adjoint"},{"category":"section","location":"#FDGrids.jl","page":"Home","text":"<p align=\"center\">\n  <img src=\"assets/logo.svg\" alt=\"FDGrids.jl logo\" width=\"640\">\n</p>\n\nFDGrids.jl provides compact finite-difference differentiation matrices on uniform and non-uniform grids. The same one-dimensional operator can be applied to vectors, matrices, and higher-dimensional arrays along any selected dimension.\n\nThe package is useful when a PDE, stability, or time-stepping code repeatedly applies the same one-dimensional finite-difference operator to many fibers of an array. It stores only the local stencil coefficients and supplies generated mul! kernels for the common application paths.","title":"FDGrids.jl"},{"category":"section","location":"#Highlights","page":"Home","text":"Finite-difference coefficients on arbitrary non-uniform nodes.\nUser-chosen odd stencil widths.\nDimension-wise mul! along any array axis.\nOrdinary and weighted adjoint operators.\nGrid constructors with matching quadrature weights.\nCompact in-place LU factorisation and generated triangular solves.\nLower-level hooks for slab-local and decomposed-domain arrays.","title":"Highlights"},{"category":"section","location":"#Quick-Example","page":"Home","text":"using FDGrids\nusing LinearAlgebra\n\ng = grid(64, -1, 1, GaussLobattoGrid())\nD = DiffMatrix(g.xs, 5, 1)\n\nu  = sin.(g.xs)\ndu = similar(u)\nmul!(du, D, u)\n\ndu[1:3]\n\nDiffMatrix behaves like an AbstractMatrix, but the dense matrix is only formed when requested:\n\nM = full(D)\ndu ≈ M * u","title":"Quick Example"},{"category":"section","location":"#Documentation-Map","page":"Home","text":"The tutorials are the best place to start:\n\nGetting Started\nDimension-Wise Differentiation\nWeighted Adjoints\nDecomposed Domains\n\nThe manual pages give a more detailed account of the implementation and mathematics:\n\nGrids and Quadrature\nFinite-Difference Operators\nAdjoints\nLinear Solves\nNumerical Methods\nInternal Layout and Kernels\n\nFor function signatures and docstrings, see the API Reference.","title":"Documentation Map"},{"category":"section","location":"#Installation","page":"Home","text":"using Pkg\nPkg.add(url = \"https://github.com/Davide-Lasagna-s-Lab/FDGrids.jl\")","title":"Installation"},{"category":"section","location":"#References","page":"Home","text":"B. Fornberg, \"Generation of Finite Difference Formulas on Arbitrarily Spaced Grids\", Mathematics of Computation, 51(184), 699-706, 1988.\nB. Fornberg, A Practical Guide to Pseudospectral Methods, Cambridge University Press, 1998.\nJ. M. López, D. Feldmann, M. Rampp, A. Vela-Martín, L. Shi, and M. Avila, \"nsCouette: A High-Performance Code for Direct Numerical Simulations of Turbulent Taylor-Couette Flow\", SoftwareX, 11, 100395, 2020.\nJ. Waldvogel, \"Fast Construction of the Fejér and Clenshaw-Curtis Quadrature Rules\", BIT Numerical Mathematics, 46, 195-202, 2006.\nG. H. Golub and C. F. Van Loan, Matrix Computations, 4th edition, Johns Hopkins University Press, 2013.","title":"References"}]
}
